By combining bacterial culture and retrospective rt-PCR assays, at least one pathogen was identified in 81 cases (95.3%). The number of detected pathogens was of 0, 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5 in 4 (4.7%), 30 (35.3%), 34 (40.0%), 13 (15.3%), 3 (3.5%) and 1 (1.2%) specimens, respectively (Table 2
). From the 85 cases of CAP, 4 bacterial exclusive infections were observed (4.7%), 24 infections with at least one bacterium and one virus (28.2%) and 53 viral exclusive infections (62.4%). Coinfection by at least two viruses was observed in 37 cases (43.5%). Table 3
displays the distribution of the identified pathogens and specifies the various associations, the most common being ADV/RSV (10 cases), Haemophilus influenzae/ADV(8 cases) and hREV/BoV (8 cases).
